items.title: Phascolarctos cinereus
items.content_text: A koala in a tree at 410 Gap Road. We hear and see them frequently here. This one gave us a great display of his stretched out neck while grunting.

items.title: Macropus giganteus
items.content_text: Watched for some time two kangaroos fighting. They were impressive looking animals. Tall and strong. The Kangaroos around them seemed to take little notice.

items.title: Pseudocheirus peregrinus
items.content_text: Cut down small dead eucalyptus tree near the house. Tree had been planted about 25 years ago. Didn't realise the centre had rotted out and this guy was living inside.

items.content_text: Soggy male. New research has suggested size of a male kangaroo's forearms is a key factor in their ability to find and keep mates.

items.content_text: Enjoying the green grass of the lawn. Perhaps 3m away from me (with me inside house, wallaby outside).

items.title: Pseudocheirus peregrinus
items.content_text: Stayed there for 10 minutes (that I saw), occasionally wandering to the other end of the window sill (3-4cm wide), then occasionally wandered back again - half fell off once but clambered back up.

items.title: Wallabia bicolor
items.content_text: Looks like a young wallaby feeding about 4-5m from us. I think this one we've seen drinking from our birdbath too.

items.title: Rattus rattus
items.content_text: Dead rat left on verandah, presumably by a cat. Last week an Agile Antechinus was left with throat punctured.

items.title: Antechinus agilis
items.content_text: Left on my verandah. Can only think it was killed by a cat.

items.title: Litoria ewingii, Pseudocheirus peregrinus
items.content_text: Possum wandered around lounge window ledge about 1.5m away from where I was sitting. It climbed window frame - looked as though it was after moths. Coincidentally two frogs on the same window.

items.title: Petaurus breviceps
items.content_text: Heard yapping in trees for a few nights.

items.title: Wallabia bicolor
items.content_text: Small joey out and about. Small body (size of a large bird) and disproportionately long tail. Didn't see the mother.
